\subsection*{7.1 Introduction}

The acceleration of population growth in the developing countries of the world has not been due to a change in the birth rates; but to the great reduction in death rate following improvements life in the developing countries, the rate of natural increase was most unlikely to have been more, and may indeed have been much less than that of the more developed countries.

There is still considerable scope for reduction in death rates in the developing countries. If this should occur unaccompanied by any fall in birth rates; the populations of these countries would grow at even faster rates than at present. In short, there is no hope of any reduction in the rates of population growth until the fall in birth rates is faster than that of the rates of death. In any case, the population will go on increasing until or unless the Crude Birth Rate (CBR) = Crude Death Rate (CDR) when the natural increase becomes zero.

\subsection*{7.2 Measurements of Mortality}

To study mortality, it is necessary to use comparative measures or indices of mortality for periods and areas under consideration. The basic measures are essentially rates of incidence relating to the number of death to a unit of population, commonly 1,000 , in a particular interval of time. The interval is invariably one year, to avoid the complicated effect of seasonal mortality variations on comparability of rates.

\subsection*{7.2.1 Crude Death Rate}

This is the simplest measure, indicating the number of deaths in a particular year per 1,000 of the population.

Formula: $-\mathrm{CDR}=\underline{\mathrm{D}} \times 1,000$
P
Where $\mathrm{D}=$ Deaths in a year
